SIMPLE: foliation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Foliation
<hw>Fo"li*a"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>foliation</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The process of forming
into a leaf or leaves.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The manner in which the young leaves are disposed
within the bud.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> The . . . <qex>foliation</qex> must be in relation to the
stem.</q> <rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The act of beating a metal into a thin plate, leaf,
foil, or lamina.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The act of coating with an amalgam of tin foil and
quicksilver, as in making looking-glasses.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>The enrichment of an opening by
means of foils, arranged in trefoils, quatrefoils, etc.; also, one of
the ornaments. See <er>Tracery</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>The property, possessed by some
crystalline rocks, of dividing into plates or slabs, which is due to the
cleavage structure of one of the constituents, as mica or hornblende. It
may sometimes include slaty structure or cleavage, though the latter is
usually independent of any mineral constituent, and transverse to the
bedding, it having been produced by pressure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Foliature</ent>⟦br⟧
